gtr:id>5D297969-4F98-4D91-837A-0573932996FF</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Abby</gtr:firstName><gtr:surname>Day</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FE016626%2F1"><gtr:id>8C8BBD7C-84CD-4108-9C29-766E5D85B4FA</gtr:id><gtr:title>Believing in Belonging: an exploration of religious belief and identity</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/E016626/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>People are increasingly concerned about how religious beliefs and identities are manifested in the UK and elsewhere. The Fellow?s doctoral research challenged and developed theory and method within the sociology of religion, relating to theories of secularisation and conceptualisations of 'belief'. The Fellow will now develop her theories and career through working with Prof. Simon Coleman as mentor within the anthropology department at the University of Sussex. She will bridge sociological and anthropological approaches to belief and engage with international networks of scholars who combine qualitative and quantitative methodologies.&amp;nbsp; &lt;/p> 
&lt;p>She will also improve three research skills vital to a professional academic: using cross-cultural research methods, understanding quantitative methods and analyses, and developing successful research funding proposals.&amp;nbsp; &lt;/p> 
&lt;p>The Fellowship will enable her to publish research in a variety of forms, from highly-specialised academic papers to more widely available newsletters and newspapers. She will work extensively on a book, write four scholarly papers and attend three international conferences.&amp;nbsp; She will further disseminate and enrich the work through engaging with wider networks of academics and users, in universities, schools, and government. &lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2009-04-30</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2007-05-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>67507</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>Believing in belonging in contemporary Britain</gtr:description><gtr:form>A talk or presentation</gtr:form><gtr:id>B784919C-5F54-4ECA-8AB4-286DB1214E8E</gtr:id><gtr:impact>Presentation to Religious Studies National Teachers' Conference,</gtr:impact><gtr:outcomeId>r-8878954163.6397652af7c384</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:partOfOfficialScheme>false</gtr:partOfOfficialScheme><gtr:url>http://www.philipallan.com/pdfs/teanatrel.pdf</gtr:url><gtr:year>2007</gtr:year></gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>Belief and identity in late modernity : transcending disciplinary boundaries : introduction</gtr:description><gtr:form>Participation in an activity, workshop or similar</gtr:form><gtr:id>5D404DCA-CF30-4DC9-96FC-E054CFB98B32</gtr:id><gtr:impact>Inter-disciplinary workshop to explore contemporary meanings of belief and identity. Organised both as Postdoc event and as annual Study Day for Sociology of Religion Study Group, British Sociological Association.</gtr:impact><gtr:outcomeId>r-7322640202.308672af43fde</gtr:outco